{
  "texts": [
    "Introduction and summary of results IntroductionThe recent developments on non-invertible symmetries hold promising potential to open an exciting chapter in the study of non-perturbative phenomena in quantum field theory (QFT).To study systems with conventional group-like symmetries, representation theory is of course indispensable, as it describes the action of these symmetries on physical states and local operators.",
    "Likewise, we will argue that the key to unlocking the full utility of generalized, in particular non-invertible, symmetries is to understand their action on local and extended operators of various dimensions.",
    "Said differently, the key is to determine the generalized charges carried by operators in a QFT with generalized global symmetries.",
    "This will be laid out in this series of papers, where the present one is the first, with subsequent followups in Parts II [1] and III [2].",
    "The role that representation theory plays for groups, is replaced here by higher-representations, which intimately tie into the categorical nature of the symmetries.Although at this point in time firmly established as a central tool in theoretical physics, historically, group theory and representation theory of groups has faced an upwards battle."
  ]
}